<!--Section: Regional-->
<section id="regional" class="section">
    <div class="container">
        <h4>REGIONAL CITIES</h4>
        <div class="row">
            <div class="span12">
                <h6 style="text-align:center; margin:auto; font-family:Brandon Grotesque; font-size: 30px; margin-bottom:20px;">
                    "We have places to live in Australia, we just haven't been very good at presenting those opportunities to people".
                </h6>
                <h6 style="text-align:center; margin:auto; font-family:Brandon Grotesque;">
                    ~ David Matthews, a 60-year-old farmer born and raised in Rypanyup, about 300 kilometres north-west of Melbourne
                </h6>
            </div>
        </div>

        <hr class="separated-line" />
        <div class="row regional-cities">
            <div class="span6" id="geelong"></div>
            <div class="span6" style="text-align:center;">
                <p>
                    <h7>Barwon Area, VIC</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <h7>Geelong</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Geelong drives its name from the aboriginal word Djillong which means ‘land’ or ‘cliffs’.
                    The region has experienced major development in the past decade in both an education sector.
                    It has also become the hub for the manufacturing industry.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align:right">
                    <a href="@Url.Action("Geelong", "City")">Explore ></a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row regional-cities">
            <div class="span6" style="text-align:center;">
                <p>
                    <h7>Loddon Campaspe Area, VIC</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <h7>Bendigo</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Bendigo has been named after an English shepherd William Abednego "Bendigo" Thompson who was famous as a knuckle fighter prize winner in the 1800’s.
                    The major industries in the region are health, finance, service, food processing, and education
                </p>
                <p style="text-align:right">
                    <a href="@Url.Action("Bendigo", "City")">Explore ></a>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="span6" id="bendigo"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="row regional-cities">
            <div class="span6" id="ballarat"></div>
            <div class="span6" style="text-align:center;">
                <p>
                    <h7>Central Highlands Area, VIC</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <h7>Ballarat</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Ballarat means ‘resting place’ in the aboriginal dialect.
                    The city has prospered in the service sector, especially tourism and hospitality. The fertile volcanic soil in the region and its climatic conditions make it suitable for agriculture.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align:right">
                    <a href="@Url.Action("Ballarat", "City")">Explore ></a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
        <div class="row regional-cities">
            <div class="span6" style="text-align:center;">
                <p>
                    <h7>Great Ocean Road Area,VIC</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <h7>Warrnambool</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    Warrnambool is the city on the south-western coast of Victoria, and marks the western end of the Great Ocean Road
                    and the southern end of the Hopkins Highway. The nearby Flagstaff Hill Maritime Village explores the area's seafaring history through a large shipwreck collection. The word Warrnambool originates from the local Indigenous Australian name for a nearby volcanic cone.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align:right">
                    <a href="@Url.Action("Warrnambool", "City")">Explore ></a>
                </p>
            </div>
            <div class="span6" id="warrnambool"></div>
        </div>
        <div class="row regional-cities">
            <div class="span6" id="latrobe"></div>
            <div class="span6" style="text-align:center;">
                <p>
                    <h7>Gippsland , VIC</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <h7>Latrobe City</h7>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The city of La Trobe is a local government area in the Gippsland region in eastern Victoria, Australia. La Trobe derives its name from the first lieutenant-governor of the state of Victoria, Australia Charles La Trobe. The city has a small-town atmosphere and is home to a vibrant and
                    walkable downtown business district with shops, restaurants, offices, and a wide range of housing options for people of all ages.
                </p>
                <p style="text-align:right">
                    <a href="@Url.Action("Latrobe", "City")">Explore ></a>
                </p>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</section>


